node.text:
Here’s what we’ve been working on  since the beginning of the pandemic early last year.

We’re so excited to announce Noma Projects and the launch of Project 001, noma’s line of garums, coming later this year. This is the culmination of 18 years of knowledge, craft and experimentation channeled into a new endeavor. To bring Project 001 to life, we collaborated with design agency @gretelnyc and one of our long-time favorite artists, @davidshrigley . For first access to preorders and news on upcoming projects, visit the link in bio! 

Music: @stefanpasborg / Ibrahim Electric
DOP: Mathias Nyholm Schmidt 
Editor: Rasmus Nyholm Schmidt

node.text: The last mouthful this year - each season it’s the same; at first the joy and delight of getting your hands on a seasonal treat. For a brief moment they were in abundance, promising to last forever. And then a little while later, they’re gone. And with it, the slight regret of not getting the most of it yet again. Will I ever learn to take in the  seasons 100%? Can I fit all of these strawberries in one mouthful?

node.text:
The element of surprise in a meal. The special extra, that can take you to a new place, has always been a foundation for our restaurant. Sometimes the surprise can be in tasting a new ingredient, a new texture or tabu foods like bugs, the list goes on and on. 

And sometimes a surprise comes in shape of the most perfect ingredients, like here with a exquisite pair of cep mushrooms, grilled over birch wood and gently brushed with mushroom garum!

node.text:
As a young boy, I have vivid memories of my mother going to friends houses for potluck dinners. My mother would always bring my fathers tomato salad: thin slices of tomato, salt and coarsely crushed black pepper, some olive oil, some vinegar, and then left to marinade for half a day. It quickly became a sensation within that friendship group. A completely normal thing to eat in the Albanian parts of the world (where my father was from), was a novelty and a delicious treat in cold Northern Denmark. Back then in Copenhagen, tomatoes and such produce, was a distant dream of far away places full of sun, no one would’ve ever thought we could have produce that could rival the most sun laden southern European country. 
The picture above is just that! More than 30 years have gone by and today we can get some of the best stuff around and every bite of ripe tomato, is to me a memory of my dear father Ali-Rami Redzepi.
